Tag every beat with two per-beat signals the writer reads later: its prose-INTENSITY
(where the prose rises vs. stays plain) and its narration SCOPE (whether it is
narrated inside the story's single point of view or steps back to a detached coda).

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}, {{ vision.tone }}. Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}.
POINT OF VIEW (the story's single viewpoint, advisory): {{ vision.pov_hint or "one limited viewpoint" }}.

This is the story's MODULATION: most beats are quiet and load-bearing; only a few
are charged. A story where every beat runs hot is exhausting to read — a plain
baseline is what makes the peaks land.

Assign each beat exactly one SCENE TYPE (Swain's beat rhythm):

- scene — ACTIVE CONFLICT. A character pursues a goal against an obstacle and the
  situation turns. This is where the prose may rise and run longer. A beat that
  COMMITS or COMPLICATES a dilemma is almost always a scene; so is any
  confrontation, decision, discovery that forces action, or reversal.
- sequel — REACTIVE PROCESSING. The decompression between scenes: a character
  absorbs what just happened, feels it, weighs it, and decides what to do next.
  Plain, shorter prose. A quiet ADVANCES or REVEALS beat is usually a sequel.
- micro_beat — PURE TRANSITION. A brief connective moment that carries the reader
  from one place or time to the next. The shortest, lowest-key prose.

Anchors for structural beats that carry no dilemma impact:
- a SETUP beat orients the reader in the world before any dilemma opens -> sequel
  by default (plain, establishing), unless it stages an active moment of its own,
  then scene.
- an EPILOGUE beat winds the story down -> sequel.

Choosing the type sets the writer's word band and intensity, so choose for
MODULATION across the whole story: a plain baseline of sequels and micro-beats
with scenes reserved for the charged turns. Do NOT label everything a scene — that
is the exact failure this pass exists to prevent.

Also assign each beat one NARRATION SCOPE — whether it can be narrated from inside
the story's single viewpoint above:

- limited — narrated inside that viewpoint. Almost every beat is limited: the
  reader is with the viewpoint character, so no other character's private thoughts
  are stated. (This does NOT forbid stating a world fact the narrator could
  plausibly know or observe — reporting the weather, a rumor, an event they witness
  is still limited; scope is about whose knowledge the narration is bound to, not
  how wide the camera pulls back.)
- wide — a detached CODA, narrated from BEYOND any single character's perception.
  Use this ONLY for a beat whose content the viewpoint character could not deliver
  at all: a world aftermath once the story's dilemmas have resolved (an event
  elsewhere, a faction's rise, a fate that unfolds over time), or a character's
  reputation or fate AFTER they have exited the story (including after death). An
  EPILOGUE beat is wide by default. A narrative aftermath or post-commit beat is
  wide only when it genuinely narrates such out-of-horizon events — if a character
  in the scene could witness or infer it, it is limited.

wide is the MARKED EXCEPTION, not a convenience: defaulting a beat to wide licenses
the writer to leave the viewpoint, so reserve it for true codas. When in doubt,
choose limited.

BEATS (in story order):
{% for r in beats %}
- {{ r.beat.id }} [{{ r.beat.beat_class.value }}{% if r.beat.purpose %}/{{ r.beat.purpose.value }}{% endif %}{% if r.effects %}; {{ r.effects | join(", ") }}{% endif %}{% if r.beat.is_ending %}; ENDING{% endif %}]: {{ r.beat.summary }}
{% endfor %}

REQUIREMENTS:
- Annotate every beat listed above, exactly once, keyed by its full beat id.
- Assign exactly one scene_type (scene, sequel, micro_beat) AND one narration_scope
  (limited, wide) to each.
